Dec 2 2007 	Personal comprehensive review of the Penthouse suite @the Jockey Club	My girlfriends &amp; I stayed @the Jockey Club for Veteran's Day weekend (Nov. 9-12) and had the MOST FABULOUS time!!! We booked a 2 bdrm/2 bath penthouse suite thru lasvegasrental.org, and for 5 girls, there was plenty of room for everyone.The things I liked:1. CLEANLINESS - It was clean and the furniture/decor seemed updated. Even the bathrooms looked like they were recently remodeled.2. THE VIEW - We had a direct view of the Bellagio water show everyday and everynight. From the master bedroom, since it was a corner unit with all windows, we had both a view of the Bellagio water show as well as the Vegas strip. We truly felt like &quot;high rollers&quot; w/out the empty pockets!3. PRIVACY - There is a one-time cleaning fee, and you don't get the daily maid service like you would in the hotels; but I thought that was better since we were only there for 3 nights. We could leave our personal, valuable belongings exposed w/out worry that there would be strangers going through our rooms.6. AMENITIES - The kitchen was fully stocked from dishwashing liquid, plateware/silverware, wine bottle opener, to extra plastic bags. The bathroom was fully stocked w/more than enough towels and Bath &amp; Body soaps, lotions, shampoos &amp; conditioners. We had 5 girls who each took showers everyday and went through a new towel each time, yet there were still new, unused towels leftover by the time we checked out. 6. PARKING - Free valet parking all day everyday. Not to mention, the valet guys were all very professional, sincere, and quick to get your car. The service was 5 star!!!7. LOCATION - Right off the strip, next to Bellagio, across from the mall... everything you need is within walking distance... what more could 5 girls ask for?Problems...I didn't really see any problems that were intolerable. I do understand the other reviews and their complaints about the noise &amp; construction, and it's true that there is some huge billion $ project being built around the hotel, but there's construction everywhere in Vegas right about now. It did look like a war zone around the hotel as you pull into the front lobby, but don't be so quick to judge. During the 4 days we stayed there (Fri-Mon), I was never bothered by the noise or construction. Not to say that I didn't hear anything, I did! But the noise was not anything so big that turning on the volume of the TV or CD couldn't fix. In fact, every night I slept with one window in the livingroom open, and had no issues falling asleep or staying asleep. Granted, we partied every night we were there, but... isn't that WHY you would go to Vegas in the first place???Perhaps most of the complaints are coming from those who stayed in rooms that were not on the Bellagio side of the building. I do believe there was more construction going on at the opposite side of where we stayed. We also stayed in a penthouse suite on the 11th floor, which I believe is their top most floor, so the location was well above and farther away from the construction noise.All in all, ABSOLUTELY I would stay there again, but I would ONLY book a penthouse suite on the Bellagio side since my experience was positive with them. I would suggest that if you plan to stay here, ask whoever you are booking through to be honest with you about the situation with the construction. Ask them which floor you'll be on, which side of the building is your room, and whether there are any cranes and construction obstructing your view. If you can book the penthouse on the 11th floor, that's going to be your best bet :)	
Nov 11 2007	Don't rule out the Jockey Club!	I feel the need to add my two cents worth on the Jockey Club.I stayed at the Jockey Club Oct 26 through 29, 2007 (we were three retired ladies, all with extensive travel experience). Given a number of reviews, we were somewhat concerned about the construction issue, and while in the throes of decision making, I spoke directly to a lady at the JC and staff at the Las Vegas Tourist Bureau. The people I spoke to were quite open about the issue and the potential for noise, but also pointed out that individual experiences have apparently been quite different, with some happy customers and some unhappy. Because our priorities were location, convenience (having kitchen facilites so we could breakfast in), and space (three in a room, and not wanting to be tripping over one another), we decided to take a chance (we were going to Vegas, after all!). We booked through the LVTB.We were in Room 1018, right beside the elevator, and facing the construction and the Monte Carlo Hotel. Rooms on the north side, where we had hoped to be, face the fountains at Bellagio. While our view was not impressive ( a number of buildings going up, and I counted over forty porta-potties, which was pretty exciting!), never once were we bothered by noise. Heavy equipment was operating below us, cranes were moving stuff, and men were laying steel below and to the right of our room. We heard the occasional banging (once that I remember) and a few beeps, but honestly, nothing bothersome.There was no work except at ground level from late Saturday pm until Monday morning.Having said all of this, it was not difficult to see that if we had been in a different room, at a different time, the noise could have been a real issue. The suite itself was spacious (large bedroom with two queen beds, double walk-in closet and full bath off bedroom, another closet and half bath off hallway, large livingroom with queen hide-a-bed, dining set, and fully equipped kitchen. It was not luxurious, but had been recently refurbished, and was clean and comfortable. Beds were great, pillows were awesome, hide-a-bed was OK. Housekeeping was OK (we didn't require much); we had lots of towels, etc.; coffee and tea were supplied. Front desk staff were pleasant and helpful, and our one and only wake-up call came right on time.Location was perfect - right beside Bellagio, across from Planet Hollywood, close to the street, with a bus stop right in front (we used the Deuce bus every day). Several times one or the other of us returned to the JC alone late at night, and felt safe doing so (lots of foot traffic, decent lighting, always staff at the side entrance, etc). The little market on the ground floor was pricey, but had more variety than the ABC store in the mall across the street (where prices were similar), and suited our needs. There was no safe in the suite, but they have bank style safety deposit boxes at the front desk -- accessible 24 hours, and very secure. Luggage storage (checkout was at 11:00, but we had a late flight) was also convenient and secure.All in all, our experience with the JC was great. Our gamble on accomodations paid off - unlike the slot machines!	
Nov 5 2007 	I'd Stay There Again-With Earplugs!	Just got back from staying there. I'd stay there again in a second Beprepared though, the Jockey Club has almost nothing you'd want in a Vegas hotel. However, it has a great location and the rooms are big and well-supplied and it's cheap and available in a pinch. If you are with your wife or a fussy friend- they will complain about the construction and dumpy hallways. But when you get to your room it's a pleasant, 1972decorated apartment setting. If you want to sleep- BRINGEARPLUGS.	
Nov 3 2007 	Loved it - Highly recommended	We stayed at the Jockey Club from 17th October until 24th October. It was through a timeshare exchange. I was a bit concerned about staying at the Jockey Club due to the reviews alot of people had posted on this site, but in my opinion people are just being very fussy. Yes there is alot of construction next to the building, we stayed on the 10th floor in room 1024, facing the construction, but at no time did the construction noise bother us. There is alot of construction at the moment in Las Vegas, just think that if you were staying on the north side of the Monte Carlo you would have a similar view, but for double the price. Any construction comments therefore cannot only be associated with the Jockey Club. The room was very spacious, contained everything that we needed, well furnished, and nicely decorated. My fiancee said the bed was the most comfortable she had ever slept in, even to the extent that she wanted to take the pillows home with us. (but didn't)We did not get to see the pool area, due to the fact that we had so many things planned during our visit..The staff at the Jockey Club were very polite and the valet parking was no problem at all. There was only one occasion that we could not park due to the lateness of our return from a show and the valet parking was full. Our solution was to valet park our vehicle in Planet Hollywood, and just walked through the casino and across the street. A walk of between 5 and 10 minutes.We had read several reviews about people having problems with taxis,picking up or dropping off at the JC. However on the occasion that we had to use a taxi to get to the JC we did not encounter any difficulty.The internet access in the lobby was a real plus point. The housekeeping was excellent (fresh towels on request). The real plus point about the JC is the location right on The Strip, everything is within walking distance and the deuce bus is very convenient to reach Downtown.We would certainly choose the Jockey Club again.	
