Oct 14 2005	Warning! Bad outweighs the good …be very careful if you are staying at the Jo	Please read this review and the ones from Sept. 7 and October 9, 2005. Everything that was said in these 2 other reviews is correct. My husband and I stayed at the Jockey Club the nights of Sept. 15 and 16. We had made our reservations through the Las Vegas Visitors Bureau, speaking to a very pleasant woman who assured me that it was a nice facility. Well, let me itemize the good and the bad.Good:1) Location. Right next to the Bellagio, across from the Aladdin and Paris on the mid-strip. You could not ask for a more convenient location.2) View. Fantastic. We had room 928, which was on the north side of the Ascot tower, facing the Bellagio. We could see the beautiful Bellagio fountain show from all the rooms, and had a great view of the Eiffel Tower at the Paris casino.3) Shampoos and soaps.4) Clean.5) Free parking.Bad:1) Furnishings. Mattresses were thin and cheap to begin with, and very old to boot. You would roll to the center of all three queen -size beds and could feel the springs poking out in several places. We asked for a change of rooms due to the mattresses, but were told that it was not possible. The sheets and blankets were thin, cheap and rough (but clean). The cleanliness of the bedspread was very questionable (cheap polyester – felt kind of greasy). The remaining furniture was very worn and outdated. The carpet in this room was clean but the cheap plastic plants were very dusty. A couple of chairs had broken arms.2) Bathrooms. Bathroom was clean, but fixtures were corroded and heavy with lime deposits. Water pressure was very poor.3) Kitchen cabinets. They were just rough-cut plywood door fronts, with a thin coat of paint. Fixtures were really old. I am glad we were not there long enough to have to rely on the cooking facilities. I saw no roaches. I do think the cleaning staff did as good of a job as they could with the old and outdated appliances, furniture and bathroom facilities and fixtures.4) Parking lot. Although the parking was free, it was a very dark area, full of pot holes and construction, and a little scary to walk through at night.When we got there late on a Thursday evening, the front desk had no record of our reservation. I did have a confirmation number, and after the clerk called the Las Vegas Visitors Bureau the LVVB faxed a copy of our reservation over and the clerk (I think her name was Hanna) gave us a two-bedroom unit for the one-bedroom price, which we had reserved. Hanna was very nice, but we never saw her again during our stay. The clerk at the front desk on Friday morning was not very helpful or nice. I would have hated to see the original unit, if the two-bedroom one was an upgrade!All in all, do not stay here if you are looking for a nice, relaxing place to stay on your Las Vegas vacation. Or, try to rent a unit from the timeshare company. DO NOT make a reservation through the Visitors Bureau! But if your back can stand an awful mattress and box springs and all you need is a place to crash for a night on your way through Las Vegas this might be the place for you.I have attached a scan of the Jockey Club layout. Also attached are a couple of photos of the view from room 928 (the view and location were the Jockey Club’s best features). The room was so depressing that I didn’t take any photos of it.	
Oct 9 2005	I cried the room was so awful	I will start with the only one good thing I have to say about the Jockey Club - the location is ace for accessing all the big hotel casinos on the strip. It is right next to the Bellagio, directly opposite the Aladdin and within minutes walk of MGM going one way, to Caesars the other. Now the bad news - everything that Tripadvisors from Columbus (Sept 7 2005) and Colorado Springs (Aug 17 2004) said about this place is true - beware Expedia customers, you will not get the fantastic rooms that are raved about in other reviews for the Jockey Club, you will get one of the tatty rooms that are owned by the Las Vegas Visitors Bureau. The carpets were so stained I counted and photographed cigarette burns, pink makeup, black marks, spills etc throughout the lounge, kitchen and bedroom areas. The furniture was scuffed really badly. And yes I can vouch that in room 880 at least there is naff '70s brown kitchenware (cooker, fridge and unbelievably, a brown sink!!) And yes, there was the ashtray. We did ask to be moved but was told that the room was 'pre assigned' and so couldn't. What was so galling is that I manged to peek into other rooms which were so much better (with white kitchenware!). Why can't the LVVB maintain their share of rooms to this standard? It's just so unacceptable. Besides this there was construction all around, one day we had to negotiate around vehicles laying new tarmac on part of the carpark. Work regularly started just under our window at 4/5am each morning. Two days running we had no water for up to 6 hrs as a) they were working on a pipeline and b) they inadvertantly broke the water pipe and to dig up the area the next day to fix it. Somehow I think you'll guess I won't be staying here again!	
Sep 7 2005	Dirty 1 star hotel - the truth about the Jockey Club	Warning: the good reviews you see about the Jockey Club are from people who stayed in the time share suites. The Jockey Club is a strange hotel. One wing of the hotel is owned by a time share company and they keep the hotel up to a 2 to 2 1/2 star level. The other wing is owned by the Las Vegas Vistors Bureau this is where the problems begin. I have stayed in hundreds of hotels in my life and this is the worst one by far!!! The carpet was horribly stained, the mattresses were broken, there was mold growing in the tub, there were chunks broken off of furniture. We went downstairs and demanded another room and were given one that was no better. They advertise themselves as a 3 star hotel when they shouldn't even qualify for a 1 star. Las Vegas Visitors Bureau side of the Jockey Club is barely habitable. Be very, very careful when you book this hotel. Make sure that you ask who actually owns the hotel suite you will stay in. If its the Visitors Bureau - don't do it! I believe that if you book directly off the internet at Expedia, Travelocity, etc... it is always a Las Vegas Visitors Bureau suite, so buyer beware online. I can't warn you enough! Don't stay here if you want a good trip to Vegas.	
