Dec 11 2004	A good value at a good location.	I won a week in a one bedroom apartment at the Jockey Club for the week of November 10 through 17 through SkyAuction. Since my winning bid was $7 (plus taxes and fees), it was a real steal. Although it is a timeshare, I never was bothered to submit to a pitch.It is an older, but fairly well maintained property. It goes back to the 1970s, when Frank Sinatra and the &quot;Rat Pack&quot; frequented there. My apartment was on the eighth floor on south side of the far building, facing a large parking lot, with the Monte Carlo in the distance. The view from the other side of the building is the Bellagio, which is next door, and across Las Vegas Blvd. was the entrance to Desert Passage at the Alladin. First, my complaints. Like the casino hotels on the Strip, there is a hike from the Strip to the lobby, and another hike to my room. I was locked out of my room near midnight one evening (the card key was changed), but the maintenance man was very conscientious in helping me out and refused a tip. Tour and shuttle buses tend to stop at the Jockey Club last, in part because there is no immediate crossover of Las Vegas Blvd. The cable connection for the TV in the living room was not secure, so I wound up using the second TV in the bedroom (fortunately, there were a couple of chairs and a small table in the bedroom).However, compensating for this, is that I doubt that one can get a one bedroom suite (or perhaps two bedrooms) in such a prime location at a lower price. There is a convenience store in the lobby which is better stocked than nearby stores such as Walgreen's, CVS, and one in the Desert Passage. Near the lobby, there are two free computers with high-speed internet connections for time-share owners and their guests.If you are not planning to prepare all your meals in your well stocked kitchen, my suggestion would be to go to the nearby Paris Casino, which has several good (French-style) restaurants at moderate prices. The MGM-Grand has purchased the nearby Boardwalk Casino and has plans to tear it down and build one continuous resort and urban community between the Bellagio and the Monte Carlo. If the Jockey Club remains in place, it will become even more desirable. If the Jockey Cub doesn't survive this development, you don't have much time to enjoy this bit of Las Vegas history at a moderate price.	
